# Backend Development Guidelines

## NestJS Best Practices

### Module Organization
- One module per domain/feature
- Register new modules in `app.module.ts`
- Register new entities in [entities.ts](mdc:apps/backend/src/modules/entities.ts)
- Register shared types/enums in `@shared` library

### Entity Design
- Use camelCase for entity class names
- Use snake_case for database column names
- Follow TypeORM conventions for entity decorators
- Keep entities focused and single-purpose

### Service Pattern
- Separate admin and frontend services
- Use dependency injection
- Follow SOLID principles
- Keep services focused on business logic

### Error Handling
- Use NestJS exception filters
- Implement proper error logging
- Return appropriate HTTP status codes
- Use custom exception classes for domain-specific errors

### tRPC Integration
- Register new routes in appropriate router files
- Protect admin routes in `admin/` directory
- Register services in `trpc.service.ts`
- Define interfaces in `trpc-services.interface.ts`

### Code Style
- Use TypeScript strict mode
- Document public methods with JSDoc
- Follow naming conventions:
  - PascalCase for classes
  - camelCase for methods and properties
  - kebab-case for files
- Avoid using `any` type

### Testing
- Write unit tests for services
- Write e2e tests for API endpoints
- Use proper mocking techniques
- Follow AAA pattern (Arrange-Act-Assert)

### Database
- Use TypeORM migrations for schema changes
- Follow migration naming conventions
- Test migrations before deployment
- Keep migrations reversible

## Code Quality
- Keep functions small and focused
- Use early returns to reduce nesting
- Implement proper validation
- Use dependency injection
- Follow SOLID principles
